  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DNA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) is a molecule that encodes the genetic instructions used in the development and functioning of all known living organisms and contains the necessary information for the organism to develop from a single cell into a complete organism."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mentioned in the context of biomolecular structure but not directly involved in the palmitoylation process."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RNA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mentioned in the context of biomolecular structure but not directly involved in the palmitoylation process."&lt;SEP&gt;"Ribonucleic acid (RNA) is a single-stranded polymeric molecule that is chemically similar to DNA but differs in several important ways, including the presence of ribose rather than deoxyribose and the base uracil instead of thymine."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ADENINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Adenine is a purine base found in nucleic acids, specifically in DNA and RNA, and is one of the four nitrogenous bases that make up these molecules."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GUANINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Guanine is a purine base found in nucleic acids, specifically in DNA and RNA, and is one of the four nitrogenous bases that make up these molecules."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THYMINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Thymine is a pyrimidine base found in DNA, and is one of the four nitrogenous bases that make up this molecule."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CYTOSINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cytosine is a pyrimidine base found in both DNA and RNA, and is one of the four nitrogenous bases that make up these molecules."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DEOXYRIBOSE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Deoxyribose is a five-carbon sugar that is a component of DNA, forming part of the sugar-phosphate backbone."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHATE GROUP&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A phosphate group is a chemical group consisting of phosphorus and oxygen atoms, commonly found in organic compounds such as nucleotides and ATP."&lt;SEP&gt;"Phosphate Group is the chemical group (-PO₄³⁻) added to proteins during phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHORYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Phosphorylation is a biochemical process in which a phosphate group is added to a protein or other substrate, often serving as a regulatory mechanism for cellular processes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Phosphorylation is the process of adding a phosphate group to a protein, which is regulated by protein kinases and phosphatases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CATECHOLAMINE OVERLOAD (PO)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Catecholamine overload (PO) is a condition involving an excess of catecholamines, which are hormones produced by the adrenal medulla."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DEPHOSPHORYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Dephosphorylation is the removal of a phosphate group from a molecule, often serving as a regulatory mechanism for cellular processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEINS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Proteins are large biomolecules composed of one or more polypeptide chains folded into a specific three-dimensional structure, playing crucial roles in various cellular functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POST-TRANSLATIONAL MODIFICATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Post-Translational Modification is any chemical alteration made to a protein after its translation, including palmitoylation, myristoylation, and prenylation, which can affect protein function and localization."&lt;SEP&gt;"Post-translational modification is a process that alters the function, localization, or stability of proteins after their synthesis, including phosphorylation and ubiquitination."&lt;SEP&gt;"Post-translational modification refers to chemical modifications of proteins after translation, such as phosphorylation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Post-translational modifications are chemical alterations to proteins after their synthesis, which can affect their structure, stability, localization, and function."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-63fa55ceeb395a1a904d11895dce16bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;UBIQUITINATION REACTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ubiquitination is a post-translational modification in which a ubiquitin protein is attached to another protein, often targeting it for degradation by the proteasome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;E1 ENZYMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"E1 enzymes, also known as ubiquitin-activating enzymes, catalyze the first step in the ubiquitination reaction, which targets proteins for degradation via the proteasome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CATECHOLAMINES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Catecholamines are hormones produced by the adrenal medulla, including epinephrine and norepinephrine, which play roles in the body's stress response and fight-or-flight reactions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ADRENAL MEDULLA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The adrenal medulla is the inner part of the adrenal gland, which produces catecholamines and other hormones."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEASOME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Proteasome is a cellular structure that degrades ubiquitinated proteins, playing a key role in the ubiquitination pathway."&lt;SEP&gt;"The proteasome is a complex of proteolytic enzymes responsible for breaking down ubiquitinated proteins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ENZYMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Enzymes are biological catalysts that speed up chemical reactions in living organisms, playing critical roles in metabolism and other cellular processes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Enzymes are biological catalysts that speed up chemical reactions in the body, often playing a crucial role in metabolic processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-abad06b263ef144df562fd23138170ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27b2d9732f29ea8f26ca0bf4e776936f</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;UBIQUITIN-ACTIVATING ENZYMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ubiquitin-activating enzymes, also known as E1 enzymes, are responsible for catalyzing the first step in the ubiquitination reaction, which targets proteins for degradation via a proteasome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN PHOSPHATASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein Phosphatase is a type of phosphatase that specifically dephosphorylates other proteins, often reversing the effects of protein kinases and regulating various cellular processes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Protein phosphatase is an enzyme that removes a phosphate group from the phosphorylated amino acid residue of its substrate protein, playing a crucial role in the regulation of protein function."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;UBIQUITIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ubiquitin is a small protein that can be covalently attached to targeted proteins, serving as a signal for their degradation via the proteasome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN PHOSPHORYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein phosphorylation is a post-translational modification involving the addition of a phosphate group to proteins, which regulates various cellular processes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Protein phosphorylation is a reversible post-translational modification involving the addition of a phosphate group to specific amino acids on proteins, primarily on Ser, Thr, and Tyr residues."&lt;SEP&gt;"Protein phosphorylation is the process of adding a phosphate group to a protein, which was first reported in 1906 by Phoebus Levene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-63fa55ceeb395a1a904d11895dce16bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3bb62c4e7ea35aeae2375f8b410bb4f9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN KINASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein Kinase is a type of kinase that specifically phosphorylates other proteins, playing a critical role in cellular processes such as signal transduction and cell cycle regulation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Protein kinase (PK) is an enzyme that catalyzes the transfer of a γ-phosphate from ATP to specific amino acids on proteins, facilitating protein phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHOPROTEOME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Phosphoproteome refers to the complete set of phosphorylated proteins within a cell or organism, highlighting the importance of phosphorylation in cellular processes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Phosphoproteome refers to the total set of phosphorylated proteins in a cell or organism, which is composed of residues accounting for 79.3%, 16.9%, and 3.8% respectively."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SER, THR AND TYR RESIDUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ser, Thr and Tyr residues are specific amino acids on proteins that are predominantly phosphorylated, accounting for 79.3%, 16.9%, and 3.8% of the phosphoproteome, respectively."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EUKARYOTIC ORGANISMS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Eukaryotic organisms are characterized by the presence of a nucleus and other membrane-bound organelles, and they utilize ubiquitination and phosphorylation for various regulatory processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CELL DIVISION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cell division is a fundamental biological process in eukaryotic organisms, regulated by various post-translational modifications including phosphorylation."&lt;SEP&gt;"cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-37640df1f633855760cc35ccbb1a5346&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IMMUNE RESPONSES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Immune responses involve a series of coordinated events that protect the body from pathogens, many of which are regulated by post-translational modifications such as phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EMBRYONIC DEVELOPMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Embryonic development is a complex process during which an organism grows from a single cell to a multicellular organism, involving numerous post-translational modifications including phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-09ba87b3011f1cff2bace9fa360f65f3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN PHOSPHATASES (PPS)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein Phosphatases (PPs) are the primary effectors of dephosphorylation and can be grouped into three main classes based on sequence, structure, and catalytic function."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHOPROTEIN PHOSPHATASE (PPP) FAMILY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The PPP family includes PP1, PP2A, PP2B, PP4, PP5, PP6, and PP7, and the protein phosphatase Mg- or Mn-dependent (PPM) family, primarily composed of PP2C."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN TYR PHOSPHATASE (PTP) SUPER-FAMILY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The PTP super-family forms the second group of PPs, characterized by their tyrosine-specific phosphatase activity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ASPARTATE-BASED PROTEIN PHOSPHATASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Aspartate-based protein phosphatases form the third group, distinct from the PTP super-family."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN PSEUDOPHOSPHATASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein pseudophosphatases are part of the larger phosphatase family, typically catalytically inert but functioning as phosphate-binding proteins, integrators of signaling, or subcellular traps."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MEMBRANE-SPANNING PROTEIN PHOSPHATASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Membrane-spanning protein phosphatases contain both active (phosphatase) and inactive (pseudophosphatase) domains linked in tandem, similar to the kinase and pseudokinase domain polypeptide structure of JAK pseudokinases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JAK PSEUDOKINASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"JAK pseudokinases have a kinase and pseudokinase domain structure, conceptually similar to membrane-spanning protein phosphatases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MANNING AND COLLEAGUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Manning and colleagues have completed a complete comparative analysis of human phosphatases and pseudophosphatases."&lt;SEP&gt;"Manning and colleagues have completed a comprehensive comparative analysis of human phosphatases and pseudophosphatases, providing a companion piece to the analysis of the human kinome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RESIDUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Residues refer to the components of the phosphoproteome, accounting for 79.3%, 16.9%, and 3.8% respectively."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;KINASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Kinases are enzymes that catalyze the transfer of a phosphate group from ATP to a substrate, often a protein, leading to phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUBSTRATE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Substrate refers to the protein that is being phosphorylated or dephosphorylated by kinases and phosphatases, respectively."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ATP&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"ATP (Adenosine Triphosphate) is the primary energy currency of cells, providing the phosphate group for phosphorylation reactions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CELL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cell is the basic unit of life, where phosphorylation and dephosphorylation processes occur."&lt;SEP&gt;"The cellular context in which palmitoylation occurs and affects protein functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIGNALING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Signaling refers to the process by which cells communicate with each other, often involving phosphorylation and dephosphorylation events."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUBCELLULAR TRAPS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Subcellular traps are roles that some pseudophosphatases can take on, acting as binding sites for signaling molecules."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BINDING SITES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Binding sites are locations on proteins where other molecules can attach, such as in the case of pseudophosphatases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIGNAL TRANSDUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Signal transduction is the process by which signals are transmitted through a cell, often involving phosphorylation and dephosphorylation events."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MAMMALS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mammals are a class of vertebrates that include humans and many other species, where the phosphoproteome composition is studied."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5d6b3b961949d622dcfe0e05d8928552</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TANDEM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Tandem is known for research in the field of kinase and pseudokinase domain polypeptide structure, particularly in relation to JAK pseudokinases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HUMAN KINOME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Human Kinome is the complete set of ~536 human protein kinases encoded in the genome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PALMITOYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Palmitoylation is a dynamic, post-translational process believed to be employed by the cell to alter the subcellular localization, protein–protein interactions, or binding capacities of a protein."&lt;SEP&gt;"Palmitoylation is the covalent attachment of fatty acids, such as palmitic acid, to cysteine and less frequently to serine and threonine residues of proteins, enhancing their hydrophobicity and contributing to their membrane association."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PRENYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Prenylation is a post-translational modification distinct from palmitoylation, involving the attachment of isoprenoid groups to proteins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MYRISTOYLATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Myristoylation is another post-translational modification distinct from palmitoylation, involving the attachment of myristate to proteins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PALMITOYL PROTEIN THIOESTERASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Palmitoyl Protein Thioesterases are enzymes that catalyze the reverse reaction of palmitoylation, breaking the thioester bond between palmitic acid and proteins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;KINASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Kinase is an enzyme that transfers a phosphate group from ATP to a substrate, often another protein, playing a crucial role in cellular signaling pathways."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PSEUDOKINASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pseudokinase is a protein domain that resembles a kinase but lacks the catalytic activity, often serving regulatory functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHATASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Phosphatase is an enzyme that removes phosphate groups from other molecules, often deactivating proteins involved in cellular signaling pathways."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PSEUDOPHOSPHATASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pseudophosphatase is a protein domain that resembles a phosphatase but lacks the catalytic activity, often serving regulatory functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THIOESTER BOND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Thioester Bond is a type of covalent bond formed between a thiol group and an acyl group, often found in palmitoylation reactions where palmitic acid is attached to a protein via a thioester bond."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4432cd18455493f56d1ebf4c8de8f45c</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OYL PROTEIN THIOESTERASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"OYL Protein Thioesterases are enzymes involved in the dynamic, post-translational process of palmitoylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Molecules that undergo palmitoylation and can have their subcellular localization, protein–protein interactions, or binding capacities altered."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BIOMOLECULAR STRUCTURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The intricate folded, three-dimensional shape formed by a molecule of protein, DNA, or RNA, important to its function."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PRIMARY STRUCTURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The sequence of amino acids in a protein."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9fb5b6385442e4d4d7212c99fb107174</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN KINASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein kinases are enzymes responsible for the enzymatic phosphorylation of proteins, discovered nearly 50 years after the initial report of protein phosphorylation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Protein kinases are enzymes that catalyze the transfer of a phosphate group from ATP to a specific amino acid residue in a protein, leading to phosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-63fa55ceeb395a1a904d11895dce16bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3bb62c4e7ea35aeae2375f8b410bb4f9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTEIN PHOSPHATASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protein phosphatases are enzymes that catalyze the removal of a phosphate group from a protein, leading to dephosphorylation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-63fa55ceeb395a1a904d11895dce16bf</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SERINE&quot;">
